# Scala Type System & Idiomatic Patterns (2.13)

## Sealed Traits for ADTs
Scala uses sealed traits (or sealed abstract classes) to model algebraic data types.
All subtypes must be in the same file, enabling exhaustive pattern matching.

"'```scala
sealed trait TokenType { def value: String }
object TokenType {
  case object STRING extends TokenType { val value = "string" }
  // ...
}
```

## Case Classes for Immutable Data
- Automatically get `equals`, `hashCode`, `toString`, `copy`
- Use `copy()` for creating modified instances (like Python'"'s dataclass with frozen=True)

"'```scala
case class Token(value: String, tokenType: TokenType, metadata: Map[String, Any] = Map.empty) {
  def withMetadata(entries: (String, Any)*): Token = copy(metadata = metadata ++ entries)
}
```

## Generics & Variance
- Covariant: `+A` (producer/output position) — like Python'"'s "'`T_co`
- Contravariant: `-A` (consumer/input position) — like Python'"'s "'`T_contra`
- Invariant: `A` (both positions)

```scala
