## Core Types
- `io.circe.Json` — the main JSON AST type (replaces Python'"'s recursive "'`JsonValue`)
- `Json.Null`, `Json.fromString(s)`, `Json.fromInt(n)`, `Json.fromBoolean(b)`
- `Json.arr(...)`, `Json.obj("key" -> value)`

## Parsing
```scala
import io.circe.parser._
val result: Either[ParsingFailure, Json] = parse("""{"key": "value"}""")
```

## Rendering
```scala
json.noSpaces   // compact, like json.dumps(value)
json.spaces2    // pretty, like json.dumps(value, indent=2)
```

## Navigation (for tokenize_path equivalent)
```scala
// Using cursor-based navigation
val cursor = json.hcursor
cursor.downField("key").as[String]  // Right("value")

// Manual path traversal
def traversePath(json: Json, parts: List[String]): Option[Json] = parts match {
  case Nil => Some(json)
  case head :: tail =>
    val next = json.asObject.flatMap(_(head))
      .orElse(json.asArray.flatMap(arr => scala.util.Try(head.toInt).toOption.flatMap(arr.lift)))
    next.flatMap(traversePath(_, tail))
}
```

## Key Differences from Python json module
- Circe is type-safe — no `Any` needed
- `Json` is the unified type (no need for `Union[str, int, float, ...]`)
- Parsing returns `Either` (not exceptions)
